Anyway, to cut a long story short I eventually I was able to go. Here‚Äôs my point: The thing that saved me was that a man walking past had stopped and was listening to the whole thing. He only said something at the end ‚ÄúAre you OK?‚Äù but that was enough.

He knew all the police language and told me what I could be prosecuted for. I told him he would need to prove it as there was no mark of a collision on my car. ‚ÄúIt could be on the tyres‚Äù he countered. All the answers, all the police language.

As I drove along Hammersmith Road I realised he was frantically signalling for me to pull over. I saw no warrant card or uniform but he looked and talked like a police officer. His anger was barely concealed and I was scared. He told me to get out of the car which I did.

A few years ago I was waiting at traffic lights at Hammersmith Broadway in my car when a motor bike came up on the inside, inches from my front bumper. This annoys me, so I made no allowance for him and pulled away normally.
